# RTK — token-optimized shell output

`rtk` is a CLI proxy that filters and compresses command output before it enters context. Use it for shell commands with large or noisy output.

## When to use rtk

```bash
rtk git status / log / diff   # git commands
rtk gh pr list / issue list   # GitHub CLI
rtk ls / rtk tree             # directory listings
rtk <any command>             # large output you need to read directly
```

## When NOT to use rtk

- Output you need to **parse in code** → use `ctx_execute` / `ctx_batch_execute` instead
- Short commands (<10 lines output) → plain Shell is fine
- Commands where rtk has no proxy (e.g. `npm test`, `python3`) → rtk passes through as-is; prefer `ctx_batch_execute` for build/test output

## Rule

> Any shell command that would produce >20 lines: either `rtk <cmd>` or `ctx_batch_execute`. Never raw Shell with large output dumped directly into context.
